The paper deals with facial action unit detection, which is a problem in computer vision. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also proposes a novel method for feature disentanglement, which involves training a model to separate the shape and texture features of facial images. This suggests that the paper could also be relevant to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper evaluates its method on a benchmark dataset (EmotioNet), which falls under the sub-category of multimedia (cs.MM). Finally, the paper discusses the potential applications of its method in human-computer interaction, which could place it under the sub-category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
